JUnit Platform must instantiate TestSuiteTest, but nested fixtures might not be instantiated by Jupiter. I wonder if all constructors of nested classes are registered unless reflection configuration includes all public methods and constructors of all classes? This could complicate things. I'll need to clarify how these registration processes work in Native Image with JUnit.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Implemented a dedicated active-class coverage test for `junit.framework.TestSuite`.\n\nAdded:\n\n- `tests/src/junit/junit/3.7/src/test/java/legacy/junit3/TestSuiteTest.java`\n\nThe new test constructs a `TestSuite` from a public JUnit 3 `TestCase` fixture with a public `String` constructor and a public `testPasses` method. This exercises:\n\n- `TestSuite` class-literal path that invokes synthetic `class$` / `Class.forName(...)`\n- `TestSuite.addTestMethod(...)` path that invokes `Constructor.newInstance(...)`\n\nI did not run or compile tests, per your instruction.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_010f8aee3d98f5ef0169f64e93e6188190834b4d9153046a12\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 435, "output": 965, "cacheRead": 38400, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 39800, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp": 1777749639801, "responseId": "resp_010f8aee3d98f5ef0169f64e8845f48190b62f048f0e7e5e90"}}
